					<physDesc rend="visible">
						<p>Parchment codex of the 14th century.</p>
						<objectDesc form="codex">
							<supportDesc material="perg">
								<extent>165 folios<dimensions unit="mm" type="leaf">
										<height>368</height>
										<width>265</width>
									</dimensions>
									<dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
										<height>180</height>
										<width>250</width>
									</dimensions>
								</extent>
								<foliation>
									<p>165 folios  (+ 2 unfoliated paper flyleaves at the beginning and 3 at the end of the codex).</p>
								</foliation>
								<collation>
									<p> 	Quires of mostly 8 leaves each.</p>
								</collation>
								<condition>
									<p>Imperfect at the beginning.</p>
								</condition>
							</supportDesc>
							<layoutDesc>
								<layout columns="2" ruledLines="25" writtenLines="25">
									<p>Uniform layout. </p>
									<p>Pencil ruling and occasionally pricking is visible. </p>
									<p>Chronicles and Esther begin a new column, and Proverbs opens a new leaf. </p>
									<p>If there is not sufficient room in a line to complete the last word, the final letter or the last two letters of the same word are placed in the margin, some vacant space being left between the columns and these letters. </p>
									<p>The number of Psalms is 151 (number 96 is divided into two parts). </p>
									<p>Few masoretic notes. </p>
								</layout>
							</layoutDesc>
						</objectDesc>
						<handDesc hands="1">
							<summary>Sefardi square script, punctuated and accentuated, of early 14th century.</summary>
							<handNote script="Hebrew" scope="major"/>
						</handDesc>
						<additions>
							<p>Several records of sale by: Yudah ben Shelomoh (seller); Eliyahu, Shemuʾel, Zidkiyahu and Avraham ben Mosheh (buyers); Shelomoh ben Yeḳutiʾel da Bethel (buyer); Benyamin ben Yoʾav (buyer); Daniel ben Yeḥiʾel  of Montalcino (buyer, inscribed with a date of <date calendar="Hebrew">5135</date>, <date calendar="Gregorian">1375</date> in <name type="place">Perugia</name>); and an attestation of Yeḥiʾel  ben Meshullam the scribe and Benyamin ben Manoaḥ to the sale of the present manuscript by the lady Brunetta, widow of Daniel of Motalcino, to Mordekhai ben Mosheh (buyer, with a date of <date calendar="Hebrew">5162</date>, <date calendar="Gregorian">1401</date> in Perugia on the Tiber); inscribed on folio <locus n="165v"/>. An English translation of the first three contracts, and an account of the last two, are attached to the paper fly-leaf at the end of the codex (<locus n="166r"/>).</p>
						</additions>
						<bindingDesc>
							<binding>
								<p>Post-1600, Harleian binding of gold-tooled brown leather. Boxed.</p>
							</binding>
						</bindingDesc>
					</physDesc>
					<history rend="visible">
						<origin notBefore="1300" notAfter="1340"/>
						<provenance>
							<p>Spain</p>
						</provenance>
						<acquisition>
							<date>1753</date>
							<p>The Harley Collection, formed by <name type="person" role="owner">Robert Harley</name> (b. 1661, d. 1724), 1st earl of Oxford and Mortimer, politician, and <name type="person" role="owner">Edward Harley</name> (b. 1689, d. 1741), 2nd earl of Oxford and Mortimer, book collector and patron of the arts. Edward Harley bequeathed the library to his widow, <name type="person" role="owner">Henrietta Cavendish, née Holles</name> (b. 1694, d. 1755) during her lifetime and thereafter to their daughter, <name type="person" role="owner">Margaret Cavendish Bentinck</name> (b. 1715, d. 1785), duchess of Portland; the manuscripts were sold by the Countess and the Duchess in <date calendar="Gregorian">1753 </date>to the nation for £10,000 (a fraction of their contemporary value) under the Act of Parliament that also established the British Museum; the Harley manuscripts form one of the foundation collections of the British Library.</p>
						</acquisition>
					</history>
